T1  - Priority Scheduling Rules for Repairable Inventory Systems
AU  - Hausman, Warren H.
AU  - Scudder, Gary D.
Y1  - 1982/11/01
PY  - 1982
DA  - 1982/11/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.28.11.1215
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.28.11.1215
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1215
EP  - 1232
VL  - 28
IS  - 11
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Improved priority scheduling rules are presented for a repair shop supporting a multi-item repairable inventory system with a hierarchical product structure. A variety of scheduling rules are evaluated using a simulation of a representative shop and product structure. The results indicate that dynamic rules which use inventory status information perform better than other dynamic or static rules which ignore inventory status; moreover, dynamic rules which use work-in-process inventory information outperform dynamic rules which ignore work-in-process inventory levels. In the simulation, the use of improved scheduling rules provides performance equivalent to a 20% reduction in spares inventory.
AB  - Improved priority scheduling rules are presented for a repair shop supporting a multi-item repairable inventory system with a hierarchical product structure. A variety of scheduling rules are evaluated using a simulation of a representative shop and product structure. The results indicate that dynamic rules which use inventory status information perform better than other dynamic or static rules which ignore inventory status; moreover, dynamic rules which use work-in-process inventory information outperform dynamic rules which ignore work-in-process inventory levels. In the simulation, the use of improved scheduling rules provides performance equivalent to a 20% reduction in spares inventory.
