TY  - JOUR
T1  - On Optimal Replacement Policies
AU  - Assaf, D.
AU  - Levikson, B.
Y1  - 1982/11/01
PY  - 1982
DA  - 1982/11/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.28.11.1304
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.28.11.1304
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1304
EP  - 1312
VL  - 28
IS  - 11
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - A system (e.g., a car) must operate for the next t time units. A certain component (e.g., a battery) must be replaced whenever it fails, as it is essential for the operation of the system. There are several types of components differing only in price and life distribution. The problem of choosing the optimal type at any time in which a replacement is needed has previously been studied when all life distributions are exponential. In this paper the results are extended to the case where life distrubutions are arbitrary. Conditions are given under which there is an optimal replacement policy with a special convenient form. Algorithms for the solution of the problem are provided. Examples and related problems are discussed.
AB  - A system (e.g., a car) must operate for the next t time units. A certain component (e.g., a battery) must be replaced whenever it fails, as it is essential for the operation of the system. There are several types of components differing only in price and life distribution. The problem of choosing the optimal type at any time in which a replacement is needed has previously been studied when all life distributions are exponential. In this paper the results are extended to the case where life distrubutions are arbitrary. Conditions are given under which there is an optimal replacement policy with a special convenient form. Algorithms for the solution of the problem are provided. Examples and related problems are discussed.
